# Spring Boot Agent Guide

## Required Quality Gate

Before considering coding work complete, run habit-hooks from the repository root.
For a tight local loop, use changed-file scope:

```bash
habit-hooks
```

Before handing back a Spring Boot change, use the full repository gate:

```bash
habit-hooks --all
```

If the installed command is unavailable, install habit-hooks or use a
project-local launcher JAR when this repository carries one:

```bash
java -jar target/habit-hooks-*-launcher.jar --all
```

For larger Spring Boot changes, run the setup check first:

```bash
habit-hooks doctor
```

After a failing run, generate focused follow-up artifacts when useful:

```bash
habit-hooks report --no-fail
habit-hooks tasks --no-fail
```

## Spring Boot Setup

`habit-hooks init --spring-boot` enables the full analyzer surface in
`.habit-hooks.yaml` and writes `habit-hooks-maven-snippets.xml`. Copy the Maven
properties, dependencies, plugins, and profiles from that snippet file into
`pom.xml`, then run:

```bash
./mvnw --batch-mode --no-transfer-progress spring-javaformat:apply
habit-hooks doctor
```

## Working Rules

- Treat every habit-hooks finding as actionable project feedback.
- Fix reported findings before moving to unrelated work.
- Create or update a task for each reported violation group.
- Do not snooze baseline entries without explicit maintainer approval.
- Do not disable Checkstyle, PMD, Taikai, or Maven-backed analyzers just to quiet findings.
- Keep Spring controllers thin, services focused, repositories persistence-only, and transactions out of controllers.

## Commit Messages

Use Conventional Commits for every commit message:

```text
<type>[optional scope]: <description>
```

Examples: `feat(web): add owner search`, `fix(service): preserve transaction boundary`,
`docs: update deployment notes`, `test(repository): cover missing entity`.

## Expected Analyzer Surface

Spring Boot projects should normally keep these analyzers ready: Checkstyle, PMD,
Taikai, SpotBugs, JaCoCo, CycloneDX, PIT, Spring Java Format, Error Prone, OWASP
Dependency Check, and JSpecify.

PIT and OWASP Dependency Check can be slow. Keep them ready and use them for
full-repository, pre-push, CI, release, or reference-validation runs; disable
them in `.habit-hooks.yaml` only when the project explicitly chooses a faster
local profile.

Use `habit-hooks tasks --format json --no-fail` when another agent needs a
structured work queue, and rerun the task's `verificationCommand` after fixing a
batch.